Sonic-Style 2D Game Engine
Description of the Program
This project is a simple 2D game engine inspired by classic Sonic-style movement. It simulates player physics such as acceleration, gravity, jumping, and movement along flat and sloped surfaces. The program uses Java Swing for rendering and provides a basic framework for platformer-style games.
The player can move left and right, jump, and interact with terrain that includes both flat ground and angled slopes. The goal of the project is to demonstrate physics-based movement and collision handling in a 2D environment.

Controls:
Left Arrow → Move left
Right Arrow → Move right
Spacebar → Jump

Features of the Program:
-Smooth 60 FPS game loop
-Player movement with acceleration and friction
-Gravity and jumping mechanics
-Collision detection with terrain
-Support for sloped surfaces (angle-based movement)
-Double-buffered rendering for smoother visuals
-Keyboard input using key bindings (more reliable than key listeners)
Data Structures Used:
- ArrayList<Surface>
 - Stores all terrain surfaces in the game
 - Allows dynamic addition/removal of level elements
 - Objects/Classes
- Player → Stores position, velocity, and movement state
- Surface → Represents terrain using two endpoints
- Vector2 → Represents 2D vectors for future physics expansion
- Primitive Variables
 - Used for physics values such as speed, gravity, and position

Algorithms Used:
1. Game Loop (Fixed Time Step)
Uses a delta timing system to maintain consistent updates at 60 FPS
Ensures smooth and stable gameplay regardless of system speed
2. Physics Simulation
Applies acceleration when movement keys are pressed
Applies friction when no input is given
Uses gravity to simulate falling
Caps maximum speed to prevent overflow
3. Collision Detection
Checks if the player is above a surface using X-range comparison
Uses vertical position (y) to detect landing
Snaps the player to the surface when collision occurs
4. Linear Interpolation (LERP)
Used in Surface.getYAt(x) to calculate the exact Y position on a slope

Formula:
y = y1 + t * (y2 - y1)
5. Trigonometric Movement
Uses cos(angle) and sin(angle) to move the player along slopes, Allows natural movement on angled terrain.